translation:
Breaking Mount Heaven's Gate, the great River rolls through;
Green billows eastward flow and here turn to the north.
From both sides of the River thrust out the cliffs blue;
Leaving the sun behind, a lonely sail comes forth.

The nation shattered, hills and streams remain;
Spring in the city, lush grass and trees sustain.
Moved by the times, flowers draw tears anew;
Parting's anguish makes even birds' songs blue.
Beacon fires burn for three months unending;
A letter from home would be gold worth spending.
My white hair thinned by anxious fingers' trace,
Too sparse now to hold a hatpin in place.
